# Complete working tree in commits

When the user asks to **commit and push** (or when finishing work that should land on GitHub), run **`git status`** first.

- **Stage and include** all relevant **new**, **modified**, **renamed**, and **deleted** tracked paths (and **newly added** files that belong in the repo), so nothing intended for the change set is left unstaged.
- Use **`git add -A`** or explicit paths after reviewing status; resolve merge conflicts before committing.
- **Do not** use `git add -f` on ignored secrets (see the separate env-files rule for `.env` / `.env.local`).

After commit, **push** so the remote matches the commit.

If the user wants unrelated work split across commits, use separate commits with clear messages instead of omitting files from the push.
